      <h2>Marketing priorities for high-AOV stores</h2>
      <p>High-AOV stores break when email treats every subscriber the same. The pressure point is longer consideration, trust, financing, and expert proof. A disciplined email marketing program must coordinate consent, lifecycle timing, product context, and margin-aware measurement — not blast more coupons.</p>
      <p>Priority plays: Extended nurture sequences; Expert proof and case studies; Financing and warranty education; Consultation booking follow-up. Document suppressions for recent purchasers, wholesale accounts, and active support cases before scaling sends.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy ranks first for high-AOV stores because lifecycle editorial beats newsletter volume: welcome by signup source, replenishment matched to consumption, winback with VIP exclusions.</p>
      <p>Klaviyo remains the benchmark when high-AOV stores need predictive segmentation and native Shopify event depth at scale. Omnisend wins when email + SMS must go live before month end.</p>
      <p>Track Consideration-to-purchase window, Financing attach rate, Consultation-to-sale conversion, Full-price purchase percentage weekly. Email ROI appears when incremental repeat purchase rises while unsubscribe and complaint rates stay flat.</p>
      <p>Buying cycle reality: 2–16 weeks; multiple touchpoints; financing and warranty decisions. Email cadence must respect that rhythm — not the marketing calendar alone.</p>
      <p>Implementation: audit consent sources in week one, launch welcome segmented by source in week two, add cart or post-purchase in week three, measure repeat purchase movement in week four.</p>
      <p>Peak season for high-AOV stores requires pausing non-essential flows, protecting VIP segments, and aligning merchandising with inbox promises — governance matters more than new app installs.</p>
      <p>Deliverability note: high-AOV stores with aggressive promos need authentication, frequency caps, and sunset policies — complaint spikes often trace to offer mismatch, not weak templates.</p>
      <p>Pair capture tools (Privy, Justuno) only when list growth is the leak; pair Postscript when SMS recovery justifies cost. Avoid three senders without a collision calendar.</p>
      <p>Read comparisons and use-case playbooks on this site for head-to-head tradeoffs and execution detail specific to longer consideration, trust, financing, and expert proof.</p>
      <h3>Where high-AOV operators leak revenue</h3>
      <p>Stranger discount after months of trust nurture. Cart recovery on configured $6K orders. Financing promo to recent full-price buyer. Consultation and marketing recovery same day. Cross-sell accessory before delivery satisfaction.</p>
      <p>Reading path for high-AOV: Sequenzy extended nurture and {segment.emailPriorities.join('; ')}; suppress active cohorts during sales; {segment.metrics[3]} as maturity KPI. {segment.buyingCycle} — trust delivery, not urgency — defines Shopify email marketing apps success.</p>
