      <h2>Extended email marketing playbook for high-AOV stores</h2>
      <p>This section is the retention magazine view of high-AOV stores: not which app has the prettiest templates, but which inbox moments actually move repeat purchase when longer consideration, trust, financing, and expert proof dominate operations.</p>
      <p>Start with consent archaeology. Map every popup, checkout, footer, SMS keyword, and partner import that feeds email. high-AOV stores often fail when giveaway subscribers receive the same welcome as high-intent product-page signups.</p>
      <p>Week-one deliverable: welcome segmented by source with suppressions for existing customers, recent purchasers, and employees. If your current tool cannot branch on signup source, that is the selection constraint — not missing AI copy features.</p>
      <p>Week-two deliverable: one recovery flow with inventory checks and discount caps documented. high-AOV stores lose margin when cart recovery treats a $35 accessory and a $350 bundle identically.</p>
      <p>Week-three deliverable: post-purchase education tied to 2–16 weeks; multiple touchpoints; financing and warranty decisions. The email should reduce support tickets and set up the next purchase — not only ask for a review on day one.</p>
      <p>Week-four deliverable: replenishment or winback with VIP exclusions. Track Consideration-to-purchase window and Financing attach rate against Shopify net sales, not only ESP attribution.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy ranks first in our high-AOV stores shortlist because agent-first playbooks compress those four weeks for lean teams. Klaviyo wins when someone owns predictive segments weekly. Omnisend wins when SMS must ship beside email immediately.</p>
      <p>Pricing discipline: model 90-day sends, not 90-day profiles. high-AOV stores with wide lists and narrow engagement punish per-contact billing — pay-per-email alternatives reward pruning and targeting.</p>
      <p>Sale-week governance: document which flows pause when site-wide promos run. Collision between welcome, cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and campaign blasts is the silent LTV killer for high-AOV stores.</p>
      <p>Deliverability preflight before peak season: SPF, DKIM, DMARC alignment, popup-offer match, sunset policies for 180-day inactives, and seedlist tests across Gmail and Apple Mail.</p>
      <p>When leaving a legacy sender, export consent timestamps and parallel-run critical flows two weeks. Attribution debates slow adoption more than template rebuilds.</p>
      <p>Final operator rule for high-AOV stores: email should feel like the store remembering the customer — product context, timing respect, and margin honesty. Pick the app your team will tune every Monday.</p>
      <p>Use the comparison hub when torn between two finalists — workflow tests beat feature matrices. Use use-case playbooks for trigger, timing, and exclusion detail on welcome, cart, post-purchase, and winback.</p>
      <p>If you only fix one thing this quarter for high-AOV stores, fix suppression logic. Recent buyers, VIPs, wholesale accounts, and gift purchasers should not receive stranger-discount language — that single change often lifts placement and LTV more than a new template pack.</p>
